    "full_text": "- [David] Ah, wordsmiths. Welcome to my shop. Here I offer only curiosities. Would you like to see? Oh, I hoped you might. The words on offer today\nare ingenious, experience, and evaluate. We'll go through their\ndefinitions, explain their origins, and use each one in a sentence. Ingenious is an adjective that\nmeans clever or inventive. Having lots of smart new ideas. Coming up with cool\ninventions or solutions. Experience, it's both a noun and a verb. As a noun, it means something\nthat has happened to you, or knowledge or skills\ngained by doing something. As a verb, it means to go\nthrough something yourself. Evaluate, it's a verb. It means to analyze or examine something in order to form an opinion about it. Let's get into where\nthese words come from. For ingenious, let's\nfocus on two word parts. In means, well, in. And gen means born or created. It's the idea of skill or\nsmarts being an inborn quality, something you've either got or you don't. For my part, I don't\nreally think that's true. I worked very hard to know\neverything that I know, and I bet you did too. Word origins aren't destiny. Just because a word has a particular origin doesn't make it true. Something to keep in mind. Related words to ingenious include, generate, to make, to produce. I can generate electricity\nfrom these solar panels. Gene. A gene is a science term. It's part of the DNA inside your cells. And genius. A genius is a brilliant person, a uniquely smart or talented person. Or you can use it as an adjective to describe a particularly brilliant idea. A genius idea. In experience, let's focus on two parts. Again, ex meaning out, and pair meaning try, or test, or risk. If you've experienced\nsomething, you've tried it out. Per, and this word is from Latin, and is different from\nthe Greek prefix per, which means through like\nin persist or persuade. Words that use these word\nparts include experiment, a process of testing things. An expert, a person who knows\na lot because they've tried and tested a great deal. And expel, to push out, to get rid of. And finally evaluate. I'm sorry that my Vs and Us\nalways look almost identical. It comes from the Latin word parts. Ex, again our old friend meaning out. Val, meaning worth or\nstrength from the Latin. While uate, to be strong, to have value. And ate, a suffix that makes\nit into a verb, an action word. So, a verb forming suffix. To evaluate something, therefore is to pull the\nvalue out of something, to analyze it. Other words with that vowel\nroot include valuable, something that's worth a lot\nof money or is very important. Something that has a lot of\nvalue, right, is valuable. Valid, something that is\nstrong or true is valid. A true statement. Or prevail, to win, to be\nstronger than your opponent. Now, let's use these\nwords in some sentences. \"We didn't have the money for\nour movie's special effect, so Robbie ingeniously used mirrors to make it look like\nthe car was floating.\" He was very clever, he was very creative. He made use of what he had. \"Marcy carefully\nevaluated the shiny stone. Was it a precious gem or\njust a piece of cut glass?\" She examined the shiny stone\nto develop an opinion about it, to determine if it was an expensive gem or just ordinary glass. \"Rohit loved driving through\nthe automatic car wash, but he wanted to experience the suds for himself outside the car.\" He wanted to go through the process. He wanted to try it for himself, to experience the feeling of\nbeing a car in a car wash. Wordsmiths, I'm so glad you\nwandered into my shop today. I'm grateful for your business. And if you want to come back, you should know we're open 24 hours. So, I'll be around if you'll be around. You can learn anything. David, out."
